Backup

partimage --nodesc save /dev/sda1 /media/backup/sda1_2010-08-31.partimg.gz - backup a partition
	sudo partimage restore /dev/sda1 backup.partimg.gz - restore a partition
tar --one-file-system -cpf /media/backup/system.tar * - backup root file system (if run from /) in single mode, or from live CD (then run from /mnt)
	tar -xf /media/backup/system.tar - restore the files (run on newly created partition), then update fstab and delete /etc/udev/rules.d/70-persistent-cd.rules and 70-persistent-net.rules; then update grub using chroot
rsync -ahrv --delete --delete-excluded --link-dest=../last / --files-from=backup-include.lst --exclude-from=backup-exclude.lst /media/backup/$(date +%Y-%m-%d) && ln -nsf /media/backup/$(date +%Y-%m-%d) /media/backup/last
	- make a copy of the specified files using hardlinks where possible via the "last" target, then make the current backup the last one with a softlink
Back in Time (rsync frontend, optional cronjob)


Fault Recovery

What to do if some application doesn't promptly respond? First, you should keep calm. Try to normally shut it down.
	After a minute or so (depending on the system load) you might let the desktop environment kill the application via window decoration's close button.
	You are likely to be asked if you really want to kill it, or to wait some more.
Anyway, you can launch your favorite task manager like top on terminal or gnome-system-monitor that allows you to watch the resources and kill or terminate applications.
If the graphical environment doesn't respond, then my next attempt would be to switch to a virtual console via CTRL-ALT-F1 or -F2, log in with superuser privileges, and to run top there.
If you aren't familiar with the console or top or simply aren't in the mood to log in, you can simply press CTRL-ALT-DEL in a virtual console to initialize a soft reboot.
A magic SysRq key combination (Alt + SysRq + some key) can send various commands to the kernel even if the system seems to be frozen.
	A common idiom to perform a safe reboot of a Linux computer which has otherwise locked up, the QWERTY mnemonic "Raising Elephants Is So Utterly Boring", "Reboot Even If System Utterly Broken" or simply remembering the word "BUSIER" backwards, is often useful:
	unRaw, tErminate, kIll, Sync, Unmount, reBoot.
	Wait a few seconds each.
	TODO: Does this work with AltGr+SysRq+Key in case Alt+Print is used for screen capture in GNOME?
