Set root password

on boot, in grub, edit command: add "1" to kernel line
the kernel will boot up to single-user mode
run the passwd command to set a new password


Access from other system (e.g. Live CD)

become root: sudo su
find partition: fdisk -l
mount partition: mkdir /media/sdb2; mount /dev/sdb2 /media/sdb2
check content: ls -a /media/sdb2
mount /dev: mount -o bind /dev /media/sdb2/dev
mount /proc: mount -t proc /proc /media/sdb2/proc
mount /sys: mount -o bind /sys /media/sdb2/sys
change root: chroot /media/sdb2


Run fsck on a TrueCrypt volume

truecrypt -d crypted.tc - dismount if mounted
truecrypt --filesystem=none crypted.tc - mount the volume without mounting its filesystem
truecrypt -l - list mounted volumes
	output will be: /dev/mapper/truecrypt0 (or similar)
	
sudo fsck -fC /dev/mapper/truecrypt0 - do the check
truecrypt -d crypted.tc - dismount
truecrypt --fs-options=rw,noatime crypted.tc mountpoint/ - remount


