Overwrite a disk with zeroes for secure deletion, and show a progress bar

# dd if=/dev/zero bs=1M | pv -s $(blockdev --getsize64 /dev/sdc) -B 1M | dd of=/dev/sdc bs=1M
You might want to use /dev/urandom instead of /dev/zero, but this would be much slower, and it doesn't make much sense.
Alternatively, you could fully encrypt the disk and forget the key.
for details, see Step-by-Step Secure Erasing of a Data Storage Device


Data Recovery

Recovery from Physically Damaged Drive

apt-get install gddrescue - gddrescue with logfiles allows to be called multiple times and rescues only what is left untried; don't mistake for dd_rescue
ddrescue -s50M /dev/hdc hdimage.bin logfile.log - rescue most important parts first: copy first 50 MB
ddrescue -s1M -r3 -d /dev/hdc hdimage.bin logfile.log - rescue important, try hard: copy first 1 MB, max-retries 3 times, direct access
ddrescue -i39G -s1G /dev/hdc hdimage.bin logfile.log - rescue end of disk (example disk would have a size of 40 GB)
ddrescue -i19G -s2G /dev/hdc hdimage.bin logfile.log - rescue middle of disk (example disk would have a size of 40 GB)
ddrescue -n /dev/hdc hdimage.bin logfile.log - rescue whole disk quickly: no-split (stop after trimming, saves much time)
ddrescue -dr3 /dev/hdc hdimage.bin logfile.log - rescue whole disk thoroughly: direct access, max-retries 3
ddrescue -dRT /dev/hdc hdimage.bin logfile.log - re-try everything exhaustively: direct access, re-trim, try-again
then you can make a backup copy of the image and mount it
see also: magicrescue to scan for lost files


Move /home to another mountpoint

check size of /home: du -sh /home
create an empty formatted partition that is large enough
log off, use terminal
find new partition: fdisk -l
mount new partition: mkdir /mnt/tmp; mount /dev/sda6 /mnt/tmp
sync content: rsync -avx --progress /home/ /mnt/tmp (cp is faster but don't guarantees consistency)
mount new /home: mount /dev/sda6 /home
check result: du -sh /home; mount|grep /home
unmount tmp: umount /home
remove old data: rm -rf /home/* (don't remove the folder itself)
get UUID of new partition: blkid|grep sda6
enter line to /etc/fstab: UUID=f72aac23-092f-4484-b35c-f222c106d716   /home   ext3   defaults   0 2
leave chroot: exit
reboot


Hide partion from Nautilus

Idea: Nautilus shows those partitions that are mounted in /home or /media. To hide them, mount (or fake-mount) them elsewhere in /etc/fstab.
UUID=12345 /mnt/dontmount1 ntfs-3g noauto 0 0


